title: Not liking the customer service and the trick fees...
reviewText: I do a ton of business through PayPal and I send my wife my balance at the end of the day and she transfers it to the bank. Of course I set it to friends and family so there's no fees between us and it stays set to that for a few weeks then randomly switches back to goods and services and hits me for an additional fee and some times I won't notice it for a few days and they're racking up bonus fees off me... I tried calling customer service and they firmly blew me off when I demanded they reverse any fees between our two accounts. When I asked to escalate the call they put me on hold up they closed (25 minute wait for me). I'm busy and this type of sneaky trickery infuriates me to no end. I've been a loyal PayPal business user for five years and I'm honestly considering switching to square over this...

title: 5+ years - Never had any issues
reviewText: Wow, just read some of the reviews and some were scary.  Sometimes people can have one bad experience and it ruins their outlook on the product or service, though one time is all it takes, right?  Maybe PayPal as a whole had some hiccups when the transfer of ownership took place.  But in all honesty, PayPal is wonderful.  Never had any issues sending/receiving money nor utilizing the funds that remained on the account to pay family, friends or vendors. And now, they offer money bank transfers, that's wonderful! When the need for cash arose the funds were easily transferred to the bank, which usually took 24 to 48 hours on a business day. For example, when the transfer request took place on a Saturday the funds where available as soon as Monday. Just be sure you allot yourself enough time for the transfer, as the free request to transfer your funds isn't instant, but do believe PayPal offers a faster option for a fee.  Happy PayPal-ling from a happy and satisfied customer. :)

title: Unsafe transaction interface
reviewText: The PayPal mobile app interface is legitimately stupid, for these major reasons: Every time I want to send someone money on the Paypal mobile app,  I need to put in their mobile number or email to find them in the system. Assuming I do not mistakenly input a wrong number or letter into one of these options, the account comes up WITHOUT a photo or a PayPal.me identification handle (paypal.me/JohnSmith ) to confirm I'm sending the money to the correct recipient. And in this state, I can actually send the money, to the number/email (hopefully not mistakenly put in) without any other identifying characteristics. Let's just take a moment to digest how patently error-prone, unsafe and absurd this process is....Only after the transaction has sent do I get to see these identification handles. In my humble opinion, seeing some other confirming information about the account I'm sending money to is critical information to see prior to the sending of that money...this would reassure me that I'm not sending it to a different account with a slightly different phone or email. title: Terrible customer service & security risks
reviewText: Two months ago, I attempted to send my friend money on Paypal with her cellphone number. After I hit "send" it showed somebody else's name that should not be connected to that phone number. I immediately tried reversing the charge but it wouldn't let me because it comes directly out of my checking account. I called customer service and emailed for help but nobody answered. I then called my bank to stop payment, which they did. I Venmo'd my friend instead and I didn't ever hear back from Paypal until today... I received a call from a bill collector stating that I owe a debt to Paypal. Figuring it was a scam, I hung up and called Paypal. They patched me through to the same bill collector and will not take my calls until I "pay the debt". I am livid!! I will never use Paypal again! They pose a serious security risk and their lack of customer service is unethical.

title: Having to rethink using PayPal !
reviewText: I do not feel that it is right to be charged a $25 fee to send a family member that is in the service $800! I do know about the friends and family deal that you have set up, however my son was not in a situation where he could wait six days for a check to clear. Due to their family emergency they needed the funds immediately. A lot of times that is the case and is what PayPal and the friends and family is set up for. I stayed on the phone with one of the representatives in your company for over an hour, and I will add that I stayed on hold when I First called in for over 30 minutes waiting to speak with someone in the beginning. And obviously that did no good whatsoever. The lady that tried to help me was very nice, however she could not speak English very well at all even though I will give her a B+ for trying. Also she was not familiar with any of your policies whatsoever every question I had she had to put me on hold and go look them up so there would be a question and another five minute hold, a question and another five minute hold yes I realize people have to train, but when doing so normally there is a supervisor or at least someone that has been on the job for a couple years sitting there beside them trying to help them and lead them through the difficult questions. I felt like this lady while giving it her best was just kind of hung out to dry. A lot of times I was leading her rather than her leading me.Really sad to say that I have started using Cash App to do most of my transactions just because it is simpler and easier to use. And it is linked directly to my bank account and I can do just as much quicker with it than I can with PayPal. 😞

title: Disappointed in service
reviewText: I sighed up with PayPaland used it as a more secure way for online transactions. I connected pay pal to my bank and bought some concert tickets. I ended up selling those tickets due to change of plans and the funds were refunded back into my PayPal account. PayPal had no trouble at all taking money from my bank to pay for online transactions, but transferring the refund back into my bank account was a total nightmare. The funds wouldn't transfer to my back. I was on the phone with PayPal customer service 5 days in a row, waiting 30 minutes to talk to a real person and each time I called no help was given to me. I was told to transfer it to family member or friend, that didn't work, I was told to cash it out, that also didn't work, I was told to call my bank. The bank said my account was open. The customer service said they tried to allow the transaction to be made on their end but nothing worked. They were unable to answer the question as to what the problem was and ran me around in circles telling to me try all these different options to transfer the money, and then I was told that all those changes I've been making on my account is what was blocking the transaction in the first place. Each day I had to wait 24 hours to try again. Finally I ordered a PayPal cash card. That finally worked. However, I was expecting that money in way sooner than PayPal was able to do so. I got charged bank over draft fees at $35 each because I had scheduled payments coming out of my bank during that time. The customer service didn't seem to really care about my problem and sent me running in circles. I understand that technical issues are out of a persons control, but the staff should at least be able to tell me by the first or second time of me calling in, to be able to provide me with the correct directions of how to fix my problem, the quickest way. This whole experience was beyond stressful. I have a hard time understanding why PayPal worked so fast and easily when they were pulling from my bank, but so much trouble transferring money back into my account. It should work the same way both ways, right?  I don't know if I'll ever use or trust these services again. I ended up loosing money, paying for overdraft fees to the bank that wouldn't have occurred if I didn't use your services.

title: PayPal & me, a love/hate relationship.
reviewText: I've had paypal myself since around 2001 when I really started using eBay to buy. And bought I did. Then I started selling. Fine, no problems. Then randomly, my account would get held. This is a huge problem when you're a seller & not too many alternatives. Then my niece who is Intellectually disables and on SSDi moved in with us & wanted to sell with me. So I had her open a PayPal for her & I to use. She did & we were selling for 3 years, no problem. I pretty much controlled the account as far as invoicing etc. She had her own bank & savings account. My mother & she had a blowout. Overnight she moved in w/her mom. They managed to get all 2000 in savings & her ckg overdrawn so they closed her checking & empty savings. For her ssdi, I added PayPal direct deposit. Then her mom told her to open a Green Dot money card. All the sudden right after ssdi went in, her account is in resolution. I call ed, we sent all her docs in. One month later a very nice man finally released her acct & said the problem was Green Dot. They have issues. Now though they put withdrawal limitations on me. Ugh. At least we can ship & use cash plus card. They were very nice each call though.

title: Most secure way to pay online
reviewText: Paypal is the best in the last few years it has transitioned into being my main way of banking. It especially proves its worth when shopping online as no matter what website or service you use to buy something - as long as you used paypal to make the purchase, your money is protected and if you ever buy something that does not match exactly how it was described to you online in the item's listing then paypal will refund you completely, this goes for any website that says they no not accept returns or refunds. Paypal also has a credit program which is separated by purchase so each purchase has its own terms and you will only be charged interest on a purchased or subscription if you do not pay off the money owed for that item within the time you have selected and the max amount of time you can choose is 40 months. you can use this to purchase items you can't pay for all at once or if you want to build your credit score. The more you use it and pay things off on time the higher your overall limits will be. Paypal can also be used like venmo to send money to friends or lend money to others with pay pal accounts (of course these transactions are not protected which is why it is only recommended for family and close friends. This is done via the paypal.me account and link you can send people who can click your link to pay you. Paypal can also be used like a normal checking account with multiple ways to add or deposit money into your account, they also have a Debit Card Paypal visa that you can get to really turn it into a standard checking account. Paypal has always been one step ahead as far as banking technology and they were the first way to pay for anything online. Don't forget there is also paypal business where you can accept credit card payments and send invoices and keep track of client and customer data and payment records. If there is any banking feature paypal does not have now, best believe they will have it soon and in most cases it will be a step above the others. The only downside is that there is no actual paypal banks to walk into and deposit cash to.

title: It’s a business
reviewText: On the one hand, I can have a little gratitude for paypal, and the service it provides. It is not without its faults, IMO. The biggest issue I have is that when you deduct from your cash stash or bank, the money comes out immediately. But, then Paypal takes its time to transfer funds to your bank (or charges you), and even occasionally puts funds on hold for weeks! It seems a bit unfair to withhold funds. Other issues include annoying multiple password/login hurdles, and exorbitant notifications. I'd rather be using XRP for peer to peer transactions, and can't wait for mass adoption.

title: Beware of heavily depending on Paypal. They answer to nothing
reviewText: Before you assume I did something wrong, realistically I didn't. I had a business and a personal account to separate finances. I sometimes sent my direct deposits to my PayPal cash personal account and then to my business Paypal (this is allowed, I asked Paypal). I bought normal things with PayPal checkout, had a few customer orders (no chargebacks or disputes ever). Yet once my 1% cash back started to accumulate per month, since I was making loads of purchases, they waited until a merchant sent me funds back on a return to limit me permanently with $6000. Unless you get the US-based customer service reps on the phone, you're probably gonna have a rude experience with a Filipino rep. And even then, the USA ones don't know why decisions were made, nor can they do anything to change it (even up to the product manager level). Incredible in 2019 that algorithms with biases answer to nobody and allow Paypal to hold onto your living wages for 180 days. In light of the AppleCard fiasco, I hope Paypal's automated actions get scrutiny and that a real human with veto powers is added. I would love to have continued to use PayPal but now I'm just filing the following, and I encourage anyone else to do so as well especially if you're unsure of where to go: file a money transmitter complaint with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) against Paypal. Also file complaints to the CFPB against The Bancorp and Wells Fargo as they hold the funds for Paypal on your behalf with their debit card products. This may lead you to filing complaints with the Office of the Currency Comptroller (OCC) and FDIC. Next, contact your attorney general or state business financial division that regulates money transfers. Also send one to the California AG, and finally file a notice of dispute addressed to Paypal's legal team, more info can be found googling for Paypal Notice of Dispute page. I wish you the best and I hope Paypal, now separated from EBay, learns yo actually treat its human customers like actual humans.

title: Super Convenient & Secure!

title: Request feature design flaw
reviewText: I am collecting money from my friends to pay for our recreational sports league. I started the process with the "Request" money feature from the app. For one friend, I received the full amount requested, as I expected (be it from friends). For two others though, fees have been applied by PayPal. This being a mistake, I called the support. Apparently, these transactions were registered as "commercial" instead of "friends and family". Only the latter are free of transaction fees. PayPal takes a commission on "commercial" transactions. Fair enough ...but how the heck does it apply to my situation??!This is where I'd like to point out that the app DOES NOT provide distinct options to request from "friends and family" as opposed to "commercial". I did it the same way for the 3 friends involved ...and the results are inconsistent! The fact that 1 transaction was "friend and family" and 2 were "commercial" then appears completely random. Yes, we are talking about real world, real money! This is a serious design flaw, that has caused me stress (be it only the call to the support line that does not understand the problem, would not admit it, and cannot explain the behavior of their product) and time. Time since, apparently, the only way to rectify the situation is to request a refund of the two transactions in question via the app (as if I wanted to ever use it again!!), and have my friends start the process again. As if it were not embarrassing enough. PayPal themselves could not "make it right" as they cannot see the problem. I cannot express how disappointed, and upset, that a design flaw in the app would cause me inconvenience while trying to use it as it (seemingly?) was intended to.

title: Disappointed
reviewText: This is a halfway decent company no doubt, but I am very dissatisfied how PayPal handled one of complaints. I had ordered a pair of soccer cleats for my son from the UK. The cleats never came in. I file a dispute with PayPal since I used the company for the order. After my dispute was filed, the person with PayPal assisting me said to me; I should try and make contact with the company. I did and the company made contact with me all via email. I then contacted PayPal and asked if I should drop my DISPUTE and they said no, let them (PayPal) handle it all. So before I ended the call; I kept my dispute active. A day later I received an email saying my dispute is dropped in favor of the company I ordered the cleats from. PayPal said the reason for is because I dropped my dispute which is I a complete lie! After calling PayPal again and arguing I didn't drop my dispute they still claim I did. I told PayPal to go and listen to their recording of my conversation with them. When I was placed on hold, and later talk to; nothing was helped towards my favor. PayPal insisted I contact my credit card company and file a dispute with them. This entire ordeal in my opinion was BS. This has been since November 2018, and even making contact with this company about my sons cleats, they said they would send me a pair for him. So far that had been a complete lie as well. I am only writing this review because I don't won't this to happen to someone else. Lastly, I'm sure this will probably bother or may even offend some Admin within PayPal which is exactly was this is intended to do.

title: PayPay holds money for several days in some cases.
reviewText: I have had a problem with PayPal holding money that's been sent to me (even by my own daughter) for several days to a week, in some cases, before allowing me to transfer it to my account, or for the person I'm trying to send it to to move it to their account.  I get the feeling that PayPal may be trying to earn interest on my money by keeping it in their bank account in "pending status" for a few days before allowing me to transfer it to my account.  It's been extremely frustrating and I now tell people trying to send me money to use Venmo instead.  I have reported this to PayPal and no one there, not even a manager, could give me an acceptable explanation for this.

title: A mind of its own
reviewText: PayPal is great when it works. Sometimes the system decides to keep your money and "holds" it when you transfer it to your own bank account. Super irritating when you need it right away and you're forced to wait anywhere from 3 to 5 days for your (own) money to be transferred. These "holds" happen randomly and per their customer service is decided by the "system" as to when it happens and for how long.  I think personally this is done so that PayPal can earn interest on the money held in their accounts. There is no reason for these holds since I've been a customer using PayPal for a long time now.  I've already verified my identity a long time ago so that's not the reason. When you ask for a reason, you get a general "the computer determines this" answer.  Also PayPal charges enormous fees for transfers and payments. Especially currency conversions. Higher than a normal bank would ever charge so be prepared to take a hit when using PayPal.

title: Great except for Anti-Gun policy
reviewText: I have been using PayPal since it started. For shopping on eBay, there is no better way to pay. Same, in my opinion, goes for paying or sending money to friends, family, and individuals. HOWEVER, their anti-gun policy is a massive negative in my opinion. If I want to use PayPal to legally buy guns and/or accessories from a reputable store, I should be able to. Their anti-gun policies do absolutely nothing to stop criminals from buying guns illegally (ie "on the street") because A) Criminals buying guns illegally don't want a paper trail so likely wouldn't use PayPal anyway and B) If you can use any app to send money to someone, then it is essentially allowing anyone (including criminals) broader access to funds. For example, a criminal illegally buying a gun or drugs, or maybe an average person acquiring the services of a prostitute, or whatever, may not have cash and of course can't use a credit card directly to pay an illegal seller/dealer. However, if they can, and choose to, use a credit card through PayPal (or any other money transfer app for that matter), they can pay for anything they want (including drugs, guns, stolen goods, etc). So like most restrictive anti-gun policies, they do nothing to prevent illegal activity (and as stated above actually inadvertently offer broader options to these individuals), and only negatively affect honest law abiding people and legitimate businesses. It's ridiculous and serves only to limit legitimate business/consumer transactions. To believe otherwise is at the very least naive. What's next, not allowing PayPal to be used to buy personalized T-Shirts if PayPal thinks they aren't PC? Can't donate/send money to political campaigns, charities, foundations, fundraisers, etc that they don't agree with? Asinine slippery slope. But that's just my opinion of course.

title: Mostly good
reviewText: App is great for buying and selling goods on eBay. Keeps you and the other party secure. Also great for sending and receiving money from friends/family. But that is also the problem with PayPal; if there is an error on either part of the parties (I.e. bad email) then you and the recipient are foisted into PayPal's feedback loop of accountability. So, my Mom sent money to my daughter for her birthday. She misspelled my email address in the transaction so it kept the $$ in limbo until she called them and verified her identity before they would process the transaction cancellation and then she had to resend the $$ to us. Hard for an 80 yr old woman to accomplish. But I've done it too. Sent payment to a friend but copied his email wrong. So now he doesn't have the cash and I have to battle the leviathan to get resolution. App should have a quick step feature to cancel transactions (by sender) to be more user friendly

I finally was called back by same number which I answered. Victoria was on the phone, of whom I was unable to understand. She kept asking me questions for security. Some over and over again. title: Using the app for money transfers is not worth it
reviewText: I've been using PayPal for years. I was always told that it was the safest way to pay for things. And in that sense of paying for goods online, it very well may be. But to use this app for "instant" money transfer (similar to apps like Venmo) it's a nightmare. My boyfriend and I had been using the app for money transfers to each other (for rent and utilities) for the past year. And PayPal will arbitrarily decide to hold our funds for weeks before releasing them. For whatever reason, the past three months consecutively both our rent and our utilities were held as "pending" for over a week, which made us late paying some of them. Because for the person sending the money, it shows that you paid it and the money is deducted from your bank account. So it's not even like you can go and pull the money out once it's in pending. But for the person receiving it, it'll show pending for up to THIRTY days. So now we either have to have an additional couple grand in our account to have just in case PayPal randomly decides to put a hold on my funds, or start using a different payment transfer app. Obviously PayPal doesn't help with any late fees their pending status accrues, and it doesn't help with our standing with our utility companies. I would suggest Venmo, which is what we'll be moving to.

title: 10+ years.... Good but disappointing as any other bank....
reviewText: I have been a PayPal user for a very very long time.  Despite my tenure as a loyal customer with 100's of transactions, the system security precautions are sometimes debilitating. Be warned... even though they say they offer an instant transfer service between the cash in PayPal account and your personal bank account doesn't mean it will happen. They can and will hold your money up to 72 hours before it transfers. To make it worse they don't tell you that they are holding your money until after the transaction completes and you can't cancel it. So effectively, PayPal can take your money from your PayPal account and hold it up for three days before it shows up in your bank account. YOUR money can just disappear. If you call customer service, they will tell you that they have no power to change it. But as someone trying to run a business, it just doesn't work to offer a 10 minute cash transfer service that doesn't always work. Consider sticking with your local bank in the future.

title: Money on hold
reviewText: I requested some money from a friend for my medicine and PayPal put my money on hold. When I spoke to a representative I was told that it was more like a request for a business transaction, so they had to put my money on hold for 30 days. What I'm trying to understand is how they assume it's for a business. Why not have it noted before a person put in a request for money that your money may be put on hold for 30 days because PayPal assume its for a business transaction. That money was for my asthma pumps. I had to wait days later to get them. I actually got really sick. PayPal put my health on the line. It's been a few weeks and my money is still on hold, but I see PayPal got their money.

reviewText: I've had an account for a long time but never used it. I started a job at home where my employer only uses PayPal to pay. 1st check was great. There was a 24 HR waiting period. Got my money. Perfect. Then I tried to get cash at at Walmart. After an embarrassing time of 10 denials, no cash. People looking at me crazy. But my account showed I had money. So I ordered the card. Got that timely. Works great. But now my paychecks are being held for up to 21 days. Because Paypal feels like it. That's crap. My bank account has been overdrawn twice now. I get paid on Monday and don't see my money for 7-10 days. That's bull. I spoke with Customer Service and they were very quick to tell me that this was industry standard. I was just as quick to explain that EVERY bank has a provision for payroll. They told me too bad. I showed them the couple of times they paid within 24hrs. They said it was my employer. I explained no bank in the US held anybody 's check for a 7 day period. They explained they can choose to hold any check they want. And so its mine.  I'm on day 7 of my final check being held with this crummy company. I'd rather deal with an organization that has enough integrity to pay people's payroll timely. Can't think of 1 PayPal employee that would be cool with their paycheck being held. Not 1. Especially twice in a row. I'm done. I will NEVER use them again. And my employer has changed how to pay us. Buyer BEWARE!! Hello CashApp!!

title: Good gone horrible!
reviewText: I have been using PayPal for many years and always had great experiences until recently! I paused my online selling and buying for about a year and a half so I wasn't using PayPal. When I recently decided to start everything back up since life had calmed down a bit I thought I was going to enjoy and have no issues since I still had the same accounts all in good standings. Well...I was so so wrong!!! I began selling and payments were deposited into my PayPal account and everything was going smoothly for the first 3 to for sales using PayPal. I was able to transfer the money instantly to my checking account and had no issues. All of a sudden the next couple of sales, in which were no different from the first ones that were released, were held for months! The explanation given was different each time I contacted customer service. I confirmed the sale, customers confirmed they were delighted with products, even went as far as calling customer service with me the seller and also the buyer on 3 way calling so that everything could be confirmed and released! Still was given multiple different answers! After a month of daily phone calls for many hours each day wasting my time as well as my customers time I finally gave up ! Eventually the money was released a little bit at a time but needless to say I am not happy and will do everything in my power to not use PayPal! There was a local news station here that did a report that even made it to good morning America! Hopefully PayPal will get their stuff together but they have lost me and many many many others due to their lies and cover ups!

title: Horrific service I am switching to Google pay
reviewText: I had a private transaction for $52, $40 for the product and $12 for shipping I was returning a $98 item that I had bought and I was willing to accept $40 for it because it did not Work but it was past the warranty time For eBay. The same company that sold me the defective ABS unit, offered to buy it back and I agreed, but then after they got it back they said that they didn't like it and that it didn't work. I told them that it didn't work and I complain that they had sold it to me and it didn't work. The seller said in an e-mail "I will accept $15. " If you send me $15 but it will help cut my losses. But I did send the $15, I don't know what happened, but I didn't hear from the seller again until he put in a claim to PayPal for $52. Even though I gave PayPal all the emails that were exchanged, PayPal went into my account and took my money and refunded it to this dishonest seller without my permission. I am not as mad about the money as I am in mad about the fact that this person has been unjustly enriched at my expense, I am furious with PayPal customer service who I contacted several times and they assured me that they would review the emails and then he could not get more than he had originally stated it was worth. I am so angry with PayPal I am removing all my transactions off of their platform. Even though I won't cancel my account in case of an emergency, I won't be using PayPal for daily or ordinary invoices and Business receipts and AirBnB - I used to use it all the time. I will not deal with a company that is so biased and square headed. I was treated unfairly and I am very angry at PayPal. Also I do not like that helpless feeling that they can swoop in and take my money at anytime they want. This guy made his refund request almost 5 months after he received the part. If that was the case I should've gotten a refund from the first time when I discovered it was defective when I paid $98. PayPal has two sets of rules and I don't like it. Be wary of PayPal because once they're in your pocketbook they can do anything they want. I don't like the feeling of helplessness and loss of control.

title: Amazing Services In All Areas
reviewText: PayPal is easy to use both on the website and via the PayPal app. It is easy to use and understand and it is easy to navigate and learn.  Also, PayPal credit is amazing and has allowed me to build my side hustle and because I use it so well and keep turning money over and paying my purchases off fast, PayPal keeps increasing my limit automatically, it's awesome.  I love that it now helps my credit score but the only thing I do not like is the interest rate.  I would like my interest rate to go down because I'm doing so well.  If I ever have to pay interest then it would end up being quite a bit.  Luckily, almost everything I buy has 6 months interest free if paid in full so I only buy something when I know I can pay it off in 6 months.  The only tip, when you go to make a payment, they will automatically apply your payment to the next item on the list and that may not necessarily be what you want to pay off first. You may want to put money towards something that will start collecting interest so you have to contact them and let them know how to allocate those funds. I think it would be nice if we could let them know where we want the money located somehow through the app, maybe put a note somewhere or let us directly allocate it ourselves.Other than that, Customer Service is actually awesome which means EVERYTHING to me... having said that, it's hard to get ahold of someone right away via in app messaging so I have found that it is easier to call because you get a real human fairly quick and they are ALWAYS kind and get the job done and get it done correctly.  PayPal customer service has been amazing and understood all of my small issues and have fixed everything that they could on their end. PayPal has given me freedom and the safety to purchase products online safely knowing that I will be protected and it has been awesome. Ebay purchases are protected and so are invoice purchases.  PayPal is amazing.  I would literally recommend PayPal to ANYONE & EVERYONE.
